ey, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, , Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1280–18 July 1327":"1280–18 juli 1327","1280–1327":"1280–1327","1280–1326":"1280–1326","1298–Female":"1298–Overleden","1310–1347":"1310–1347","1230–1308":"1230–1308","1246–Female":"1246–Overleden","18 Jul 1326":"18 juli 1326","1230":"1230","18 July 1327":"18 juli 1327","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1347":"1347","1246":"1246","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1298":"1298","about 1310":"circa 1310","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England":"Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, , Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1280–18 July 1327":"1280–18 July 1327","1280–1327":"1280–1327","1280–1326":"1280–1326","1298–Female":"1298–Deceased","1310–1347":"1310–1347","1230–1308":"1230–1308","1246–Female":"1246–Deceased","18 Jul 1326":"18 July 1326","1230":"1230","18 July 1327":"18 July 1327","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1326":"1326","1347":"1347","1246":"1246","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1298":"1298","about 1310":"about 1310","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England":"Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","Cheadle, , Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Massey was born in 1280, in Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England, her father, Hamon de Massey VI, was 50 and her mother, Mary Beauchamp, was 33. She married Roger Dutton de Cheadle in 1300, in Cheadle, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died on 18 July 1327, in Cheadle, Cheshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1280–18 July 1327":"1280–18. juuli 1327","1280–132